1fw.title: Utility function
1fw.clickbait: The only coherent way of wanting things is to assign consistent relative scores to outcomes.
1fw.text:
A utility function is a way of preferring or wanting things that assigns coherent scores to outcomes.  For example, eating vanilla ice cream might have a score of \$5, eating chocolate ice cream might have a score of \$8, and eating no ice cream might have a score of \$0.  (The symbol '\$' is sometimes used to denote units of utility, but this doesn't mean that only money has utility.  For example, effective altruists often take Quality-Adjusted Life Years to be the key units of utility.)  Since properly utility functions only weigh total outomes, adding a constant to a utility function implies the same behavior.  E.g., if eating vanilla ice cream has a score of \$6, eating chocolate has a score of \$9, and doing nothing has a score of \$1, this is the same utility function and it creates the same behavior - we still prefer a gamble of (90% chocolate, 10% nothing) to a bet of (100% vanilla) and we still prefer a gamble of (100% vanilla) to a bet of (60% chocolate, 40% nothing).  Similarly, multiplying all the utilities by 10, or any other positive constant, doesn't change our preferences over gambles.  Thus a utility function really measures the *relative intervals* between outcomes.  A utility function doesn't have to be about what we see as real value; "count the paperclips in an outcome and that's how much you want it" is also a coherent utility function.

Several important [ coherence theorems] show that having a consistent utility function (or behaving in a way consistent with having a utility function) is equivalent to avoiding self-defeating or circular behaviors; e.g., spending all your money on plane tickets because you prefer being in Berkeley to Oxford, prefer Manhattan to Berkeley, and prefer Oxford to Manhattan.  If we can order not only your preferences over cities, but your preferences over probabilities of being in cities, in a way that prevents this from happening, then this and similar coherence desiderata imply that your behavior must be viewable as corresponding to some utility function.

7hh.title: Coherent decisions imply consistent utilities
7hh.clickbait: Why do we all use the 'expected utility' formalism?  Because any behavior that can't be viewed from that perspective, must be qualitatively self-defeating (in various mathy ways).

7ry.title: Coherence theorems
7ry.clickbait: A 'coherence theorem' shows that something bad happens to an agent if its decisions can't be viewed as 'coherent' in some sense. E.g., an inconsistent preference ordering leads to going in circles.
